edanken und mittelalterliche Perspektiven zu zwei Paradigmen am Schnittpunkt von Memoria und Geschichte -- tIndex: Millennium-Studien zur Kultur und Geschichte des ersten Jahrtausends n.Chr.0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aKarl Valentin once asked: "How can it be that only as much happens as fits into the newspaper the next day?" He focussed on the problem that information of the past has to be organised, arranged and above all: selected and put into form in order to be perceived as a whole. In this sense, the process of selection must be seen as the fundamental moment - the "Urszene" - of making History. This book shows selection as highly creative act. With the richness of early medieval material it can be demonstrated that creative selection was omnipresent and took place even in unexpected text genres.The book demonstrates the variety how premodern authors dealt with "unimportant", unpleasant or unwanted past. It provides a general overview for regions and text genres in early medieval Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aDamnatio memoriae. 4aFrühmittelalter. 4aGeschichtsschreibung. 4aKulturelles Gedächtnis. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  adamnatio memoriae.  aearly middle ages.  ahistoriography.  amemory.1 aBlennemann, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDepreux, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEber, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsders, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGanz